Document Model

  • SDK
  • Document Model

    • About MyScript Document Model

    MyScript Document Model delivers the MyScript Document Model technology, enabling creation, powerful editing and recognition of digital ink based documents.

    In brief, MyScript Document Model supplies:

    Item Description Location
    API for C, Java and .NET Document Model API edk/your_programming_language/
    MyScriptDocument The specific library engine/
    CreateDocument, LoadSaveDocument, LoadMetadata, EditMetadata, StoreMetadata, PageEdition, LayoutEdition, UndoRedo, PageUpdateListener, TextRecognition, TextIndexation, InkSearching, ShapeRecognition, MathRecognition, DocumentAnalysis These source code samples show you how to implement various use cases with Document Model edk/your_programming_language/examples/document/

    Application blueprint

    MyScript Document is used to create, edit or run recognition processes on the ink data contained in a document. The workflow that you can rely on when using MyScript Document is the following:

    1. Create a document object. MyScript Document models a document as a document object. Among other elements, this stores page objects containing the ink.

    2. From this document object, you can manipulate, edit ink and pages, analyze ink, recognize ink, modify the layout and the appearance of the document, etc.

    3. You can also be notified of any change in the document through the callback methods supplied in this SDK.

    Environment

    The main objects of MyScript Document Model are described hereby (more detailed descriptions can be found in sections addressing specific use cases).

    Document

    A document models a set of papers with written or printed information and multimedia items. It contains:

    • a sequence of pages,

    • a collection of Objects,

    • metadata information that stores data describing the document (for instance, a version tag).

    Page

    A page models one sheet of the document object. It is associated with the following elements:

    • digital ink that describes the ink strokes on that page. Read MyScript Ink to learn how this ink is represented.

    • a layout,

    • a content,

    • index files that store data required for ink search queries within the page,

    • metadata that store user defined information,

    • multimedia items, also called Objects.

    Content

    Each page is associated with a content, that is used to store recognition process inputs and results. That content can contain several contentField instances. How to set recognition processes inputs and how to get their results is described in Recognizing.

    ContentField

    A contentField contains the input and the result of a recognition process. It is defined by a unique string identifier, and a recognition type, that indicates which recognition service must be used with this field. Input items of a contentField are inkStroke instances from an ink instance.

    Ink

    An ink models the digital ink. Among others, it contains components such as inkStroke objects. ink can be recognized with MyScript Document if included in a contentField object. Read MyScript Ink documentation to know more on the ink model.

    ContentProcessor

    The contentProcessor manages recognition processes onto all the contentField objects of a document.

    Layout

    A layout describes the elements within a page (ink strokes, images, etc.) associated with their rendering information. It can contain several layers that describe themselves a collection of layout items. The layout also contains a viewport, pens, fonts, transforms, guides.

    Objects

    A document is associated with various Objects1 that can be any text or binary file, e.g. images, audio files, scripts, html files, etc.

    Objects can be referenced by a page (e.g. in its layout description). They are not linked to a given page, so 2 page instances can reference the same object. Objects can also be stored without being referenced in any page, for example to store application-specific data.

    The objectIterator allows to access the Objects.

    Objects are identified by an url, that is defined when adding an object to a document. That url is used as an identifier to reference the objects within the document. A url can be a file name, with or without sub-directories, or it can be a simple identifier.

    Following strings are valid objects urls:

    • header/company.png

    • foo/bar.txt

    • music.mp3

    • background

    • images/flower

    • user/background/flowers/orchid.jpg

    Creating a document

    Creating a document following these steps:

    1. Load or create a new document using the createDocument method.

    2. Set the temporary directory using the setTemporaryDirectory method.

    3. Add a new page through the addPage method.

    4. You can save the document using the save method.

    Check File structure section to know the way a document is stored on the disk.

    Documents and pages can store metadata information, as MyScript JSON objects. The default metadata set at document level is the following: "format-version" : "4.0". This indicates the document file format version. There is no default metadata set on pages.

    Accessing pages or objects

    You can access page instances of a document from their position in that document. To achieve this, the API provides you with various methods, among which are:

    methods description
    getPageCount returns the number of pages in the document
    getPageAt returns the page at the specified index in the document
    getPage returns the specified page in the document
    addPage adds a new empty page at the end of the document
    addPageWithInk adds a page that contains a given ink
    removePage removes a page
    movePage moves a page

    You can access Objects of a document from their url. MyScript Document provides you with the following methods to do so:

    Methods Description
    addObject and removeObject adds or removes Object from a document
    containsObject checks if an Object is included in a document
    extractObjectTo extracts an Object from the document to a given file path
    getObjects gets the complete list of Objects within the document

    Layout and rendering

    You can manipulate the layout information associated with a page for editing or rendering.

    The layout of a page describes the content of a page and how it should be displayed on the screen (pen colors, image position and size, etc). MyScript Document Model offers various ways to work on the layout. Here is a possible workflow:

    1. Load an existing document using the method loadObjectFromFile.

    2. Set the temporary directory with the method setTemporaryDirectory.

    3. Get the page you want to edit using the getPageAt method.

    4. Get the layout of this page using the getLayout method.

    5. Get the ink object of this page using the getInk method.

    6. Apply an edition or a rendering method. You can add/transform items, add/remove layers, add pens, access the bounding box of the entire layout, a layer or a layout item (through the extentProviderinterface), display the layout.

    Check the following sections to know more on the layout and to learn guidelines for performing specific editing/rendering operations on the layout.

    Elements of the layout

    Apart from the layer, there are other important objects contained in the layout. This subsection presents these elements that can be contained in the layout.

    Layout

    The layout content is stored by Z order. Layers and the layout items can be iterated following their Z order. Here is a visual example of the content of a layout:

    Layer

    As illustrated by the figure, a layer is a set of layout items. It is described by:

    • a unique identifier

    • a background color, as a RGBA value, that indicates the color of the back of this layer - default color for all layers is 0xFFFFFF00 (transparent white)

    • a sequence of layout items, sorted by Z order (first layout item is the layout item at the back of the layer)

    Layout item

    There are three available layout item types in the layout of a page. Layout items are contained in layer instances.

    Layout items Description
    Strokes layout item This associates a portion of ink with styling information. It is described by an ink tag ID that references an ink portion and a pen ID and a font ID that defines how that ink portion should be drawn.
    Object layout item This defines the position of an object. It is described by its url, the position and size of the object in the layout (x, y, width, height), an (optional) transform ID, that refers to the transform applied on the object position, an (optional) mime type that describes the content of that object (e.g. audio/mp3)
    Guide layout item This defines the display of an existing set of guide lines as defined in the content. Guide lines can not only provide spacial hint that improves the recognition task, but they can also enhance the immersion feeling of the writer. It is described by the ID of the guide, as defined in the content, and the ID of the pen to be used to render the guide lines.

    Viewport

    The viewport describes the area covered by the page layout. MyScript Document does not automatically change the layout viewport, it is up to you to modify it, according to your needs.

    By default, viewport is set to:

    x = 0
y = 0
width = 0
height = 0

    Transform

    Object layout items may be associated with a transform ID. As several layout items may share the same transform, transform matrices are stored at the layout level and identified by an ID at layout items level.

    While object layout items are associated with a transform, this is not the case for strokes layout items as the transformations applied to strokes layout items is already stored in the ink.

    Pen

    A pen is associated with one or more strokes layout items, it describes how the associated ink should be drawn:

    • the ink color, as a RGBA value,

    • the ink width,

    • the smoothing algorithm to be used on the ink before rendering,

    • the name of the brush to be used to draw.

    Font

    A font defines the set of properties such as weight, size, color to design characters. It is described by:

    • the family, that indicates the font family,

    • the weight,

    • the size,

    • the lineHeight, that is the amount of space above and below inline elements,

    • the style, that indicates whether the typeface is normal, italic or oblique,

    • the variant, that indicates whether the caps typeface are normal, small.

    Adding an inkStroke drawn with a new pen/font

    Here is an example of how to add an inkStroke to a layout, drawn with a new pen/font:

    1. Get the ink and layout of the page.

    2. Create a new empty ink tag and retrieve its tag ID.

    3. Add the new pen to the layout.

    4. Create a new font and add it to the layout.

    5. Add a new strokes layout item to the target layer, that references the ink tag ID, the pen ID and the font ID.

    6. Create the inkStroke.

    7. Add this inkStroke to the ink, specifying the ink tag ID so that inkStroke is tagged.

    Check the code sample LayoutEdition to learn how to implement this (/edk/your_programming_language/examples/document/).

    Adding an inkStroke drawn with an existing pen/font

    Here is an example of how to add a new ink stroke to a layout, on an existing strokes layout item:

    1. Get the ink and layout of the page.

    2. Get the ink tag ID associated with the target strokes layout item.

    3. Create the inkStroke.

    4. Add this inkStroke to the ink, while specifying the strokes layout item ink tag ID, so that the ink tag is extended to include this new inkStroke.

    Adding an object

    Here is an example of how to add an Object to the layout of a page:

    1. If the Object is not yet stored in the document, add it to the document as a document object

    2. Add a new object layout item to the to the target layer with the following parameters:

    • the url of this new object, as defined when it was added to the document

    • the position and size in the layout

    • although it is possible to associate an existing transform with a new Object, it is advised to keep the transform ID NULL at object layout item creation and to apply transforms afterward via a page selection

    Rendering a page

    Here is an example of how to draw the content of a page:

    1. Get the ink and layout of the page

    2. For each layer in the layout:

    • draw the background of the layer (as specified by its background color)

    • for each layout item in the layer:

      • if it is a strokes layout item:

        • get the layout item tag ID

        • get the inkSegment for that tag ID

        • get the pen associated with layout item pen ID

        • draw the ink strokes referenced by that ink segment, with the rendering parameters described in the pen

      • if it is an object layout item:

        • get the object size and position

        • if a transform is associated with that layout item:

          • get the object transform ID

          • get the transform matrix associated with that transform ID

          • apply the transform matrix on the object position

        • draw the object (if relevant) at the computed size and position

    Rendering a page selection

    Page selections implement the same interfaces as a layout (although no layout modification is allowed on a page selection), so you can render a page selection exactly like rendering the layout of a page.

    Editing

    You can edit the following pages components:

    • ink: you can add new strokes, tag strokes, etc,

    • content: you can manipulate input and results of recognition processes.

    You can also edit the layout to define ink or images layout information. Check the section Layout and rendering for more details on the layout.

    Editing a document involves the following steps:

    1. Load an existing document using the method loadObjectFromFile.

    2. Set the temporary directory with the method setTemporaryDirectory.

    3. Get the page you want to edit using the getPageAt method.

    4. Get the layout of this page using the getLayout method.

    5. Create the pageSelection that the edition operation should be processed on. A pageSelection represents a portion of the layout of a given page. You can use it to manipulate layout items and corresponding ink, images and objects. Create a pageSelection from the page using the createPageSelection method.

      At creation, your pageSelection is empty. To modify it with a selection modifier, see the operations below.
      A pageSelection object is associated with one page only. It cannot contain items from another page.

    6. Selecting a page layer is optional since it is also possible to apply the edition operation on the entire page. In this example, we suggest the scenario in which we select the page layer to modify. There may be several layers placed on the top of each other on a page. You can choose the target layer that will undergo the edition operation. To do so, you need to get an iterator to parse the list of layers, using the method getLayers. Then, you can select the layer using the selectLayers method.

    7. Apply the edition operation. You can erase, chop, paste and so on, from the available edition methods.

    You can parse the layers and layout items in the pageSelection, the same way as a layout. However, you cannot edit the layout from a pageSelection object.
    You can retrieve the inkSelection (see MyScript Ink documentation) corresponding to a given page selection, to perform operations directly on the ink.

    Selection methods

    There are different ways for you to set the pageSelection.

    Operations Description
    selectAll selects the entire page
    selectNone empties the selection
    selectRectangle, selectCircle, selectPolygon selects the page ink and layout items contained inside a geometric shape. Selection shape must overlap entirely an Object to select it, while a strokes layout item may be selected partially
    combine selects another selection
    hit selects the topmost item the closest from a given point, if that item belongs to a group, then the entire group is selected
    selectLayer selects a layer
    selectItem selects a layout item

    Once you have set the pageSelection, use directly the IInkSelection interface to manipulate the ink contained in this pageSelection (this avoids having to call a method to actually get the ink within the pageSelection).

    You cannot partially select Objects.

    Due to the binary nature of these operations, three steps are required to achieve the operation result. The operation is referred to as the modifier. The three steps consist in:

    1. Defining the current selection (the first operand of the operation),

    2. Defining the modifier (the operation to be applied),

    3. Defining the operation selection (the second operand of the operation).

    For each of the aforementioned operations, except selectAll and selectNone, a modifier must be set. This modifier indicates how the current selection must be combined with the operation selection:

    • SET: the new selection will contain only the operation selection.

    • UNION: the new selection will contain the union of current selection and operation selection.

    • INTERSECTION: the new selection will contain only the intersection between current selection and operation selection.

    • DIFFERENCE: the new selection will contain the current selection from which the operation selection has been removed.

    The following figure depicts the modification operations explained above.

    You cannot partially select Objects. If a selection overlaps an Object, it is entirely selected.
    The content of a pageSelection is automatically updated to match the modifications that are made to the page. For example, if a pageSelection contains a layout item that gets removed from the page, that layout item is automatically removed from that pageSelection.

    Handling ink component

    You can select layout items. When you select an Object, it is entirely selected: you cannot select a portion of an Object.

    This is not the case for strokes layout items: a pageSelection may contain partial strokes layout items, i.e. a strokes layout item may be marked as selected, while only part of the ink portion it refers to is selected:

    • when performing a geometric shape-based selection, only the portion of ink that is included in the geometric shape will be selected.

    • when performing a hit selection, only one stroke will be selected rather than the entire ink portion corresponding to a strokes layout item.

    Page selection allows you to retrieve the portion of a stroke layout item that is selected, as an inkSegment (see MyScript Ink documentation) with the getSelectedSegmentForItem method.

    Handling groups

    You can group (and ungroup) layout items so that they cannot be selected separately. To select a group with a geometrical selection, all the layout items of that group must be in the selection area. On the other hand, a hit selection on an item belonging to a group will select the entire group. Groups may contain layout items or other groups, in this case the parent group must be selected in order to select the grouped items.

    Edition methods

    Erase

    erase method deletes the content of a pageSelection. If some layout items or ink tags become empty following this operation, they are automatically deleted.

    Paste

    Paste operation copies the content of a pageSelection from a page into another page.

    If the page data to copy belongs to another document, selected Objects are automatically imported and their url remains unchanged. Layout data related to the pageSelection, such as pen descriptions or transforms associated with its layout items, are also copied.

    When an Object pasted from another document has the same url as an Object that is already in the destination document and if the two objects are not binary same, then the pasted object url is automatically prefixed with a hash.

    Transform

    transform method applies an affine transformation to a pageSelection.

    The transformation is described by a matrix, which is a set of 6 float values {a,b,c,d,e,f} and the transform of a point (x,y) is computed as follows:

    x’ = a*x + b*y + c
    y’ = d*x + e*y + f

    MyScript Document provides helpers that apply the following operations to a transform matrix:

    These helpers also enable basic operations on the matrices:

    • setIdentity: resets the matrix to identity,

    • multiply: combines two transforms,

    • inverse: computes the inverse transform.

    Moving layout items

    MyScript Document allows you to move the layout items of a pageSelection using the following methods:

    Method Description
    bringToFront moves the layout item from its current position in the layout to the front.
    pushToBack moves the layout item from its current position in the layout to the back.
    moveToLayer moves the layout item to the top of a given layer, whatever its current layer is.

    Recognizing

    You can perform handwriting recognition on the ink data contained in a document if this ink is included in a contentField.

    Here are the main steps to achieve handwriting recognition with MyScript Document model:

    1. Create a contentProcessor. The contentProcessor handles the multi-threading involved in the recognition tasks. Use the createContentProcessor method to create the contentProcessor.

    2. Create a listener. A listener provides notifications on different events on the document. To do so, create a contentProcessorListener using createUserObject and register it as a VO_IContentProcessorListener through the registerInterfacemethod. Attach the listener to the contentProcessor using the addListener method. Check here to know the notification cases.

    3. Configure the recognition types that you want to enable in the document. Indeed, you can perform various recognition types in a document. A configurationManager object allows specifying the enabled recognition types and customizing the recognition performances by adding setting details (resources to use, data format, etc.). First, use the method getConfigurationManager to obtain the configurationManager automatically instantiated when creating the contentProcessor. Then, specify the path of the configuration file to rely on using the method addSearchDir. Check here to know more on configurations.

    4. Load an existing document using the loadObjectFromFile method. Or, you can create a new document with pages and ink strokes.

    5. Get the page you want to apply the recognition on using the getPageAt method.

    6. Get the content of this page through the getContent method. Each page is associated with a content object, that is used to store recognition process inputs and results. That content contains contentField objects that are each associated with a given recognition type.

    7. Use an existing contentField or create a new one through the addNewField method. Provide this method with the type of this contentField. For instance, in this example, to perform a text recognition, you specify VO_CONTENT_FIELD_TEXT.

      Indicate the configuration to use with this contentField. Use the setConfiguration method to do so.

    8. Define the ink selection that will undergo the recognition. You need to define the input of the contentField. To do so, create an inkSelection2 and set it as described in MyScript Ink.

      Feed the contentField with the inkSelection using the addItems method. This adds the ink to be processed in the contentField.

    9. Run the recognition using the process method, indicating the required action. In this example, the action is VO_ACTION_RECOGNIZE.

    10. Get informed when the recognition result is ready. When a recognition result is available, you are notified by the contentProcessorListener through the callback method onResultAvailable. You can implement this callback method according to your needs.

    11. Get the recognition result. The recognition result is in a form of a pageChangeSet object. It is a patch containing all the changes to apply to the content according to the recognition process. You can apply the changes to the content using the method apply. This method returns the state value of the pageChangeSet.

    If you have removed portions of the ink that are referenced in a contentField result, you will not be able to retrieve the ink ranges associated with this recognition result, as that ink is missing. Recognition candidates can however still be accessed.

    PageChangeSet

    The pageChangeSet is a patch gathering all the changes to apply to the document, based on the recognition result. When you call the method apply, you get back the new state of the pageChangeSet:

    State value Description
    PAGE_CHANGE_SET_ERROR indicates that the patch could not be applied
    PAGE_CHANGE_SET_APPLIED indicates that the patch has been successfully applied
    PAGE_CHANGE_SET_PROCESS_REQUIRED indicates that the patch could not be applied entirely, call process method again
    PAGE_CHANGE_SET_NEW_PATCH_PENDING indicates that the patch could not be applied entirely, a new patch will be provided automatically by the contentProcessor
    If you perform several calls to the method process before having applied a recognition result with the method apply, you still get one single pageChangeSet object that includes the recognition results for this whole set of requests.

    Configuration management

    When you want to perform a recognition task on a document using the contentProcessor as presented in Recognizing, you need to set a configuration. This is because the contentProcessorrequires the list of enabled recognition types as well as customized setting specifications (resources, data format, etc.) .

    To do so, use the configurationManager API. When you create a contentProcessor, a configurationManageris automatically instantiated. There are different ways for specifying configuration details to the configurationManager:

    • indicating the path to one or more configuration scripts, using the method addSearchDir,

    • passing directly the configuration features as a string, using the method configure.

    Configuration script

    A configuration script gathers one of more different configuration items. Here is an example:

    Bundle-Version: 1.0                                    //name of version
Bundle-Name: MyConfiguration                           //name of bundle
Configuration-Script:                                  //path of resource files
  AddResDir ../../resources

Name: text-standard                                    //name of configuration item
Type: Text                                             //type of recognizer to use for this item
Configuration-Script:                                  //path of resource files
 AddResource en_US/en_US-ak-cur.res
 AddResource en_US/en_US-lk-text.res

Name: math-standard                                    //name of second configuration item
Type: Math                                             //type of recognizer to use for this item
Configuration-Script:                                  //path of resource files
 AddResource math/math-ak.res
 AddResource math/math-grm-standard.res

Name: music-standard                                   //name of third configuration item
Type: Music                                            //type of recognizer to use for this item
Configuration-Script:                                  //path of resource files 
 AddResource music/music-ak.res
 AddResource music/music-grm-standard.res

Name: shape-standard                                   //name of fourth configuration item       
Type: Shape                                            //type of recognizer to use for this item
Configuration-Script:                                  //path of resource files                 
 AddResource shape/shk-standard.res

Name: textIndexer-standard                             //name of fifth configuration item       
Type: Text                                             //type of recognizer to use for this item
Configuration-Script:                                  //path of resource files                 
 AddResource en_US/en_US-ak-cur.res   

Name: analyzer-standard                                //name of sixth configuration item       
Type: Analyzer                                         //type of recognizer to use for this item
Configuration-Script:                                  //path of resource files                 
 AddResource analyzer/ank-standard.res   
 AddResource analyzer/shk-standard.res

    The configuration script presented above specifies six different configuration items. This example allows performing recognition on four different content types: TEXT, MATH, MUSIC, SHAPE and ANALYZER contents.

    The set of configuration items is identified by the Bundle-Name field.

    As presented, you can assign a Name to each configuration item which allows you to designate the item that the contentProcessor should use when recognizing a given contentField.

    You can determine the recognizer type to use in the Type field and enumerate the resource files to use. Check Recognition types to know the different recognizer types and the associated resource types.

    Finally, you can specify commands for each configuration item. Supported commands are:

    Target Syntax Arguments
    All AddResDir DIRECTORY A search directory for resources
    AddResource FILE A resource file name
    Text Recognizer and Text Indexer DiscardCaseVariations FLAG A boolean value
    DiscardAccentuationVariations FLAG A boolean value
    SetCharListSize N An integer value between 1 and 20
    SetWordListSize N An integer value between 1 and 20
    SetTextListSize N An integer value between 1 and 20
    SetSpeedQualityCompromise VALUE An integer value between 0 and 255
    SetOverrideAccentuationScheme SCHEME Either STRICT_ACCENTUATION or LAX_ACCENTUATION
    SetOverrideCasingScheme SCHEME Either LEGACY_CASE, or STRICT_CASE, or LAX_CASE
    SetSpellingDistortion VALUE An integer value between 0 and 255
    SetGlyphDistortion VALUE An integer value between 0 and 255
    EnableOutOfLexicon FLAG A boolean value
    SetCharacters STRING A UTF-8 string containing the character subset
    TextIndexer SetSizeAccuracyCompromize VALUE An integer value between 0 and 255
    Shape Recognizer SetRejectDetectionSensitivity VALUE A decimal value between 0 and 1
    SetScratchOutDetectionSensitivity VALUE A decimal value between 0 and 1
    SetModelDetectionSensitivity MODEL VALUE The model name and a decimal value between 0 and 1
    ShapeBeautifier SetAlignmentStrength VALUE A decimal value between 0 and 1
    SetCongruenceStrength VALUE A decimal value between 0 and 1
    SetConnectionStrength VALUE A decimal value between 0 and 1
    SetBeautifierAlignmentStrength VALUE A decimal value between 0 and 1
    SetBeautifierCongruenceStrength VALUE A decimal value between 0 and 1
    SetBeautifierConnectionStrength VALUE A decimal value between 0 and 1
    Math Recognizer SetScratchOutDetectionSensitivity VALUE A decimal value between 0 and 1
    Music Recognizer SetScratchOutDetectionSensitivity VALUE A decimal value between 0 and 1
    Analyzer SetProcessingLevel LEVEL Either STROKE_TYPE, or TEXTLINE, or RECOGNITION, or BEAUTIFICATION, or ALL
    SetTextRecognizerConf BUNDLE NAME The bundle name and the configuration name
    SetShapeRecognizerConf BUNDLE NAME The bundle name and the configuration name
    SetShapeBeautifierConf BUNDLE NAME The bundle name and the configuration name

    Configurer

    You can also use the configurer API to set a configuration. The configurer is automatically created when the contentProcessorhas been configured using the configurationManager. It aims at overwriting existing configuration scripts and collecting runtime messages from the configurationManager.

    Its API provides the following methods:

    Methods Description
    getConfigurationManager returns the configurationManager that created this configurer
    getConfigurable returns the configurable object on which the target configurer applies
    apply applies the specified configuration script
    exec executes the specified configuration script
    getMessages retrieves the error messages
    clearMessages clears the error messages

    Recognition types

    Here is a summary of the required resources, recognizer and result types for each contentField type:

    Content field type Resources Recognizer Result Reference
    Text Alphabet Knowledge, Linguistic Knowledge, Subset Knowledge Text or TextIndexer Recognizer RecognitionResult MyScript Text
    Shape Shape Knowledge Shape or ShapeBeautifier Recognizer ShapeDocument MyScript Shape
    Math Math Alphabet Knowledge, Math Grammar Knowledge Math Recognizer MathNode MyScript Math
    Music Music Alphabet Knowledge, Music Grammar Knowledge Music Recognizer MusicScore MyScript Music
    Analyzer Analyzer Knowledge, Shape Knowledge, Alphabet Knowledge, Linguistic Knowledge Analyzer Recognizer AnalyzerDocument Analyzer
    Using MyScript Shape via MyScript Document involves use cases slightly different from those used in the separate MyScript Shape SDK. In particular, while you can call API methods like addXXX (addStroke, addPrimitive), from the recognition result interface in MyScript Shape SDK, this is not allowed when using MyScript Shape via MyScript Document. Instead, you add the strokes and primitives as ink into the page (using addStroke and addPrimitive) and then to the contentField input (using addItems).
    In a similar manner, when using MyScript Analyzer via MyScript Document, you cannot add strokes from the interface of the recognition result, but rather from the contentFieldinput mechanisms. This is because MyScript Shape SDK and MyScript Analyzer SDK consider input and result data as a single component while it is not the case in MyScript Document environment.
    Transliteration is not available when using MyScript Text via MyScript Document Model.

    Content processor actions

    When you run the recognition process with the processmethod, you can specify the contentProcessors action:

    contentProcessors actions Description
    VO_ACTION_RECOGNIZE requests a recognition of the contentField
    VO_RECOGNIZE_THEN_BEAUTIFY requests a recognition followed by a beautification of a SHAPE contentField
    VO_ACTION_INDEX requests a indexation of a TEXTcontentField
    VO_ACTION_RECOGNIZE_AND_INDEX requests a recognition followed by an indexation of a TEXTcontentField
    By default, recognition of scratch out gesture through the content processor is disabled because the scratch out sensitivity property is set to 0. However, you can modify this property value by configuring the recognizer in the onCreated content processor callback method, or you can use MyScript Gesture.

    Getting notified

    A MyScript Document monitors the modification on pages and ensures consistency between a page ink and its content field objects.

    To be automatically notified when a change occurs, you can implement a listener and register it to the target object that you want to monitor (page, pageSelection or contentProcessor).

    MyScript Document Model offers several ways to monitor the changes that occur on a page content, on a page and on a page selection.

    On content processor runtime changes

    When you run a recognition with the contentProcessor, you can monitor changes applied to contentField instances by attaching a contentProcessorListener to the contentProcessor. You will be notified through callback operations of the contentProcessorListener interface. Here are the main notification cases:

    Method Notification case
    onCreated a contentFieldProcessorhas been created
    onConfigured a contentFieldProcessor has been configured
    onProgress a recognition process is on progress
    onResultAvailable a recognition result is available
    onError an error occurred

    On page changes

    To monitor changes on a page, say when the portions of a displayed page must be refreshed, the pageUpdateListener can be used. A pageUpdateListener will be notified when a change occurs in the associated page thanks to the following callback methods.

    Method Notification case Useful for
    onLayoutUpdate The page layout has changed
    Returns the extent of the modifications, the layer on which the modifications occurred    		 Use this notification to update the rendering
    onContentFieldUpdate The input of a content field has changed Use this notification to trigger a call for a new recognition
    onContentFieldResultUpdate The recognition result of a content field has been applied Use this notification to trigger a typesetting process

    Given these callback methods, you can use the pageUpdateListener to detect any elements addition or removal from the content fields.

    If modification occurred on several layers, the listener will be called once for each modified layer, as modification extent will differ.
    If no layout information is associated with a page, the page update listener will not be notified of changes made to the page, as no layer nor layout information are associated with the modifications.

    On selection changes

    You can monitor changes applied to a given pageSelection, either because of an operation on that pageSelection or because the page itself has been modified (e.g. parts of its ink have been erased). This is done via a selectionChangeListener. Notification will indicate if the change was due to a transform operation only or to another operation (for example if a layout item has been removed).

    See here for more details MyScript Ink.

    Multithreading

    You can build multithreading-based applications thanks to the mechanisms implemented in MyScript Document, provided that you carefully design your program so that threads run at simultaneously without inferring with each other.

    Here are a couple of points to absolutely obey at risk of causing crashes:

    • Only the thread used when creating the contentProcessor can interact with this contentProcessor. If you try to call the contentProcessor via an other thread, you will get an error.

    • We strongly recommend to access/process the document within the same thread. In case you are not able to do so, use the mutual exclusion mechanisms provided in the API through the methods lock() and unlock().

    • Callback methods provided in MyScript Document Model API can be called by different threads. You can implement the callback methods according to your needs. However, it is strictly forbidden to implement any process acting on the document within these callback methods.

      Callback methods are not meant to process the document, but to provide pieces of information only.

    • Document and page manipulation actions may require heavy processing so, in order not to stall the calling thread, some of the actions performed on documents and pages involve background processing (adding an object to a document, extracting an object from a document, getting ink from a page, getting layout or content from a page, saving a document or a page, etc.). These actions run in a background thread and a completion indication is sent when that background processing is over. MyScript Document provides the sync() method to synchronize with the pending operations, to wait until they are over. However, you should never use the method sync(), unless it is for testing purpose. Using sync() implies your thread to wait for the achievement of an internal MyScript Document process. This could be disastrous in a real context of use since the background processing possibilities would be inhibited by sync().

      In case you are in a testing context of use and you plan to use sync(), you should never call this method within a callback method at risk of creating a deadlock scenario.

    Undoing and redoing

    MyScript Document provides History Managers to handle undo/redo of document modifications, at page level or at document level.

    History Managers allow:

    • determining whether it is possible to undo/redo,

    • undoing and redoing changes,

    • grouping several actions so that they can be undone/redone with a single call to undo/redo: startTransaction indicates that a series of modification starts, commit indicates that series ends.

    History Manager has a limited history depth for performance reason, which means that after a given number of modifications has been achieved, the oldest modifications cannot be undone anymore.

    Although it is possible to mix undo/redo operations at page and at document level, it is advised to stick to a single history manager when possible.

    You cannot undo/redo metadata modifications because metadata operations are not monitored by the History Managers.

    Ink Search

    You can index and query handwritten content.

    Indexing a page

    To run indexation on a page or portion of the page from a MyScript Document:

    1. Create a Text contentField.

    2. Fill the contentField input.

    3. Run a Text Indexer process on that contentField, using its contentFieldProcessor interface.

    The Text Indexer process stores the indexation results in the document, however contentField result is not filled by the Text Indexer.

    Parsing the indexation data of a document

    You can access pages indexation data at document level. Document provides you with means different from MyScript InkSearch, to query and parse the indexation results. To parse the indexed data from a document:

    1. Define a MyScript documentFinder.

    2. Define a MyScript InkSearch query.

    3. Pass the query to the process of the documentFinder.

    4. Some partial results and state of the process can be handled using the callback associated to the documentFinder.

    5. Result of the query is a documentFindResult that can be parsed using an documentFindOccurrenceIterator.

    The occurrence iterator enables to retrieve the following information, for each ink portion that matches the query:

    • the page that contains that ink,

    • the contentField,

    • the matching inkSegment,

    • the label associated with this occurrence,

    • the recognition score,

    • the query index, that indicates the part of the query that matched (in case of a complex query).

    Advanced use

    TextInspector

    Once you have run a recognition on a TEXT contentField object, MyScript Document allows creating text result based pageSelection with the textInspector. This is meant to be more convenient than the classic selection creation which could potentially cut out strokes belonging to characters, as illustrated below.

    To create such text result based selections, MyScript Document introduces the textInterval object. The textInterval designates the space covered by a set of characters. It is thus defined by a starting position, that is the starting character, and an ending position that is the ending character.

    A textInterval whose starting character and ending character are the same is referred to as a cursor.

    Each character is indexed to define the interval values describing the textInterval objects. Space and return carriage also have indices.

    The textInspector interface provides various methods to create and model a text result based selection via the textInterval object. Here is a typical workflow that you can rely on to create a text result based selection:

    1. Create a textInspector object. This gathers information regarding the text result based selection (for instance, associated page, associated contentField, textInterval objects, etc.). To do so, use the method createTextInspector.

    2. Define a textInterval. Use one of the available creation methods to obtain a textInterval object.

    3. Set the selection to obtain the pageSelection object. To do so, use one of the selection methods available in the textInspector API. The example above uses the method select.

    4. Once you have the pageSelection object, you can manipulate it according to your needs. For instance, you can parse the recognition result associated to the selection using getCharAt, getWordAt or getLineAt methods.

    Creation methods

    There are various ways to create a textInterval depending on your purpose. You can create a textInterval to model:

    • a cursor,

    • a single selected character,

    • one or several selected characters.

    Cursor and single selected character

    You can model cursors or single selected characters through a textInterval object specifying a geometric position that will match the target cursor location or the character. Given a geometric position, hit and getCursor return the textInterval whose interval value corresponds to the indices of the matching characters:

    • Use the method hit to create a textInterval representing a single character. In the example below, hit would return a textInterval whose interval value is [6-7].
    • Use the method getCursor to create a textInterval representing a cursor. In the example below, getCursor would return a textInterval whose interval value is [7-7].
    hit and getCursor take the contentField that the textInspector is associated to as an argument. If you do not indicate the associated contentField, MyScript Document tries to find the most probable contentField according to the provided coordinates. If there is any ambiguity, it chooses the topmost layer contentField.
    One or more selected characters

    You can model one or several selected characters through a textInterval object using fromField or fromSelection methods:

    Method Description
    fromField returns a textInterval whose interval boundaries correspond to the text from the target text content field
    fromSelection evaluates a selection and create the textInterval whose interval boundaries correspond to the text from this selection
    Expanding a textInterval boundaries

    Expand a existing textInterval boundaries using the expand method. Define the outer limits of the expansion using a textBoundary value (WORD, CHAR, LINE orTEXT).

    Selection tools

    The textInspector interface provides various ways to set the pageSelection:

    Set the pageSelection from an existing textInterval object with the select method. You can also specify the selection modifier as an argument of this method.

    TextInspector and recognition result

    There are several methods provided with the textInspector interface for you to exploit the recognition result related to a textInterval:

    Method Description
    getLabel returns the label associated with the specified textInterval
    getCharAt returns information about a character at the specified location
    getCharCount returns the number of characters associated with the specified field within the target textInspector
    getWordAt returns information about a word at the specified location
    getWordCount returns the number of words associated with the specified field within the target textInspector
    getLineAt returns information about a line at the specified location
    getLineCount returns the number of lines associated with the specified field within the target textInspector
    getCharacterSegment returns the segment containing the character candidates related to the begin position of the textInterval
    getWordSegment returns the segment containing the word candidates related to the begin position of the textInterval

    Typesetting

    Typesetting is currently available for TEXT and SHAPE content types only.

    Once you have run a recognition, say on a TEXT contentField, you can replace the handwritten field by the recognized glyphs (or primitive if you have a ShapecontentField). As presented in MyScript Ink, a glyph is defined by its bounding box. When MyScript Document provides you with a glyph from a recognized ink, its bounding box matches the location of the associated ink portion. Consequently, if you replace the handwritten portion directly with the glyphs, you could end up with overlapping and/or non-aligned glyphs, as illustrated below. In other words, you need to change (i.e. edit) the typesets geometry according to your needs.

    Here is a possible way for typesetting recognized ink (glyphs or primitives) fields. The arrangement will thus replace the associated portion of ink with the applied typeset data.

    1. Get the typeset data. Use the method getTypesetDatato do so, providing the contentField and pageSelection the recognized ink belongs to. This returns the typesetData object that contains all the information regarding the typeset for the given pageSelection.

    2. Get the number of typeset items to parse. The typesetData contains typesetItem objects that matches ink units (characters or primitives).

    3. Edit each typesetItem as you want. Use the method getItemAtto access a typesetItem. The typesetItem represents either a glyph or a primitive, whose geometry can be edited. Depending on its type, the API provides different editing methods. So, first get the type of the typeset item using the method getType. Use the method setPrimitiveData if the typesetItem is a primitive, use setGlyphGeometry if it is a glyph.

    4. Once you have edited all the typesetItem objects according to your needs, you can apply the typesetting to the page. You can replace the strokes with their typeset counterpart in the layout by setting keepLayoutto true- otherwise, by default, the typeset glyphs and primitives will not be referenced in the layout (it is up to you to add them to the layout item that you want). The apply method returns the old pageSelection corresponding to the handwritten field location and the new pageSelection corresponding to the typeset field.

    5. You can delete the handwritten field and replace it with the typeset field once you got the results of the apply method.

    Adding guide lines

    Guide lines aims at improving the recognition task by providing spatial hint to the recognizer instances.

    • A guide line set is first defined on the content, using the addGuide method from the content interface.

    • You can then reference it in one or more contentField object(s), using the addGuide method from the contentField interface.

    • You can also choose to render the guide line set in the page layout (check Pages Layout and rendering to do so). This step is not compulsory since a simple background image may be used to emulate a notebook style. In this latter case, you will need to align the background image to the guide line set.

    Guide line sets can only be added to Text and Music contentField objects. While adding guide line set is optional for Text contentField objects, it is mandatory for Music contentField objects.

    As depicted in the figure below, a guide line set has different properties:

    • a type. This specifies whether the set is horizontal or vertical.

    • a purpose. This specifies whether the set is meant to be a text baseline, a text midline, a text ascender, a text descender, a music staff (in which case the number of lines is fixed)

    • a data field that stores:

      • y0 or x0: the position of the zero-indexed line.

      • dy or dx: the offset between two consecutive lines.

      • count: the number of lines in this set.

      • first: the index of the first line (it can be negative).

      • (x1 and x2) or (y1 and y2): the position of the beginning of the lines and the position of the end of the lines respectively.

    Getting inkSegment objects

    At the page level, it is possible to get the inkSegment associated with:

    • some items from a contentField result.

    • layout item objects.

    The function isObjectAssociatedWithInkSegment indicates whether an ink segment is associated with this item and getInkSegmentForObject provides that inkSegment.

    You can also get the inkSegment associated with a textInterval object. The API of the textInspector provides two methods to do so (getCharacterSegment and getWordSegment).

    Temporary directory

    MyScript Document allows you to define a temporary directory location when creating a document.

    Defining a temporary directory is mandatory when you use Objects in the document.

    That temporary directory is used when you save documents and pages: a sub directory is created when you save a document to temporary folder, named by appending -files to the documents file name (e.g. mydoc.notes-files). If you have set no temporary directory, that sub directory is created in the same directory as the document.

    That sub directory is removed when you save to document or when you discard of the document modifications.

    No temporary directory setting is required when you work on a document that is not going to be saved to disk.

    Saving

    You can save changes made to a document to disk with MyScript Document:

    • at page level: modifications on a given page are saved.

    • at document level: all modifications on all edited pages are saved.

    MyScript Document keeps track of modified elements and writes to disk only the modified items, to ensure optimal performances. : MyScript Document allows you to save changes in 2 ways:

    • saving to temporary directory: saves data to the temporary directory. This does not modify the original document, so as not to interfere for example with cloud storage synchronization services. Modifications saved to temporary directory can be discarded via a discardChanges operation. When loading an existing document, modifications stored in the temporary directory are taken into account

    • saving to document: saves data to the document itself. Modifications that have not been saved yet (to temporary directory or to document) are saved into the document. Modifications that have been saved to temporary directory are also saved into the document, and the temporary directory is cleared

    Saving to temporary directory stores some files into file system, while saving to document involves compressing these files and modifying the documents zip container in the file system, which can be process intensive.

    So, while saving to temporary directory is not mandatory, it provides better performances than saving to document.

    Moreover an auto save feature can be enabled at document level. It allows the document to automatically save the modified elements when the document or a page is released.

    Documents and pages grooming

    In order to keep documents size on disk as small as possible, it is necessary to remove unused data from the document on a regular basis.

    At document level, objects and pages that have been deleted by the user are not actually removed immediately, to allow undo/redo of such modifications. These items will be automatically removed from the document file next time that document is loaded.

    At page level, layout and content cleanup is not automatic, it must be explicitly requested via a cleanup operation that parses the page data and removes unnecessary items, for example:

    • Layout pens that are not referenced in the layout.

    • Strokes layout items that refer to an ink tag that does not exist anymore in the ink.

    • Strokes layout items that refer to a style that does not exist.

    • Objects layout items that refer to an object that has been removed from the document.

    It is advised to run page cleanup operation for example before saving, when shutting down the application.

    Documents and pages memory offloading

    In order to keep document memory footprint as low as possible, the document periodically checks if some of its cached data (such as ink, metadata, content and layout) has been unused for some time and can be offloaded from cache.

    When the data to offload from cache has been modified but not saved, the document will automatically save it to temporary directory, so as not to lose any modification.

    If no temporary directory is associated with the document or if the memory offloading to temporary directory is not activated, modified data will not be unloaded from cache, until document is saved (to document or to temporary directory).

    Modifications stored in the temporary directory, either at user request or by the document offload mechanism, can be discarded via a discardChanges operation.

    Synchronous recognition

    As presented, in Recognizing, it is highly recommended to use the contentProcessor object for handling recognition processes, in particular when performing incremental recognition. However, in certain cases, you may prefer to handle threadings, recognizers configuration etc. by yourself. In that cases, you will make use of the contentFieldProcessor objects. Then, the recognition process via MyScript Document is very similar to a regular recognition process (i.e. without a MyScript Document Model).

    The following example shows the main steps for running a synchronous recognition with MyScript Document Model. In this example, a Text recognition is performed.

    1. Load an existing document using the method loadObjectFromFile.

    2. Set the temporary directory.

    3. Get the page you want to apply a recognition on using the getPageAt method.

    4. Get the content of this page through the method getContent. Each page is associated with a content object, that is used to store recognition process inputs and results. That content contains contentField that are each associated with a given recognition type.

    5. Add a new contentField through the method addNewField. In this example, it is a Text contentField.

    6. Build the input item that will feed the contentField. You can add and remove input items to a contentField input via a pageSelection, an inkSelection - that can be retrieved directly from a page selection - or via an inkSegment. In this example, we propose to create a pageSelection. Create a pageSelection from the page using the createPageSelection method. Set this selection using one of the API selection methods.

    7. Add this selection to the contentField using the addItems method.

    8. Create a recognizer. In this example, you create a textRecognizer since the contentField type is TEXT.

    9. Load and attach the specific resources. Depending on the type of recognition you run, you need to attach specific resources that configure the recognizer. In this example, load and attach text resources (Alphabet Knowledge -AK-, and Linguistic Knowledge - LK).

    10. Once you have set the contentField input, you can pass this contentField to a recognizer for processing. Run the recognition process through the contentFieldProcessor interface using the method process. The textRecognizer processes the input items contained in the contentField.

    11. Get the recognition result. The recognition result of the processed contentField input can be retrieved from the contentField interface using the getResult method. The structure of a contentField result depends on the contentField recognition type.

    Check the code samples provided at edk/your_programming_language/examples/document/ to learn more.

    Check the different recognizer types and resource types here.

    File structure

    This subsection addresses the storage format of the different elements forming a document. Documents are stored as zip archives. The storage format is illustrated by the figure below.

    As said above, a Document contains a sequence of pages and a collection of objects, which are described in the Document index file.

    Each page can contain digital ink, metadata, layout and recognition content descriptions.

    All types of Objects are stored in the Objects folder (any text or binary file, e.g. images, audio files, scripts, html files, etc.). Objects can be referenced by a page in its layout description, but they are not linked to a given page, so two pages can reference the same object.

    Standard file extension for a MyScript Document is .notes.

    Document root directory

    Location

    /. (root directory of the container)

    Description

    The Document root directory contains the following items:

    • /

      • index.xml : the Document index file,

      • meta.json : the Document metadata file,

      • pages/ : the pages directory, that contains pages descriptions (each page is then stored under a directory named after its ID),

      • objects/ : the objects directory that contains Document objects.

    Document index file

    Location

    /index.xml

    Description

    The Document index file contains the list of objects stored in the Document and the description of the pages sequence (mapping between page position and page ID). Only elements that are referenced in this index will be accessible to users.

    There are different elements in the index file, with various associated attributes:

    • pages lists the pages by page position (page 0 first, then 1, 2, etc.) test

      • id is the page identifier, generated at page creation, it is used to internally identify each page. Note that the ID is not visible from user side: pages can be accessed by their position only.

      • pages also contains a list of InkSearch index, each associated to a content field identified by its field ID.

    • objects lists the objects stored in the Document.

      • url is the url provided by user when adding an object to the Document. This url is relative to ./objects directory in the Document structure, i.e. an object with url=image/picture.png will be stored at ./objects/image/picture.png in the Document.

      • hash is a hash value computed on the entire file, when the object is added to the Document. It is used internally for fast file comparison.

    Example

      <?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?>
  <document xmlns="http://www.visionobjects.com/ns/myscript/document">
    <pages>
      <page id="aa0ae97b" />
      <page id="aa0e5c35" />
     <index field="myTextField1"/>
     <index field="myTextField2"/>
      <page/>
      <page id="aa107dfb" />
      <page id="aa12de22" />
    </pages>
    <objects>
      <object url="person.png" hash="51760208" />
      <object url="extra/readMe" hash="12345678" />
      <object url="audio/background/music.mp3" hash="5897654" />
      <object url="script.sh" hash="98755346" />
    </objects>
  </document>

    Document metadata file

    Location

    /meta.json

    Description

    This metadata file is meant to store information that is common to all pages, in JSON format. By default, the following metadata info is set:

    "format-version" : "4.0"

    Example

    {
  "format-version": "4.0",
  "title": "A Christmas Carol",
  "creation-date": "2013-02-05",
  "authors": "Charles Dickens",
  "lang": "en-US"
}

    Objects directory

    Location

    /objects/.

    Description

    This directory contains the objects referenced in the Document index file.

    The path of each object, relative to the objects directory, is determined by the url provided by the user when adding that object into the Document. That url is also used as identifier to reference the object within the Document, e.g. in the Document index file and in page layout description.

    Url can be file names, with or without sub-directories, or it can be a simple identifier. Following strings are valid objects url:

    • header/company.png

    • foo/bar.txt

    • music.mp3

    • background

    • images/flower

    Pages directory

    Location

    /pages/.

    Description

    This directory contains the sub-directories that describe each page, which are named after the page ID, e.g.:

    • /pages/

      • abcdefgh/ : the description of the page which ID is abcdefgh

      • bghadgep/ : the description of the page which ID is bghadgep

    Page directory

    Location

    /pages/abcdefgh/. (where page ID  = abcdefgh)

    Description

    A page directory contains the pages description.

    Each page directory contains the following items:

    • /pages/abcdefgh/

      • page.xml : page index, that stores the description of page (including layout and recognition content).

      • ink.jink: page ink description.

      • meta.json : page metadata information.

    If a page has been created but not edited (i.e. page is empty and has no metadata), the page directory will not exist.

    Page index file

    Location

    /pages/abcdefgh/page.xml (where page ID = abcdefgh)

    Description

    The page index describes page content and layout.

    Page content

    The content element of page index describes the inputs and results of recognition processes that have been run on the page.

    Content is split into fields:

    • a field is identified by a unique, user-defined ID (e.g. myTextRecognition).

    • a field is named after the recognition engine it is associated with: textField, shapeField, mathField, musicField etc.

    Each field contains the following nodes, whose format differ depending on the recognition engine it is associated with:

    • input: the description of an input to the recognition process, typically one or more tag IDs that reference portions of the ink.

    • xxxResult: the description of the corresponding recognition process output, where xxx identifies the recognition engine (text, shape, math, music, etc).

    Page layout

    The layout element of page index describes how ink, images and other objects should be rendered.

    Layout consists in layers, each containing several layout items that may have the following types:

    • strokes: references a portion of the ink.

    • object: references an object stored in the Document, identified by its url.

    • group: contains a set of layout items that have been grouped so that they can be easily selected and modified together. A group may contain other groups.

    Layers and items are stored by Z-order, so that a simple iteration on layout content also indicates the order in which items should be displayed.

    Following information can be retrieved from the layers:

    • an ID (for example a layer could be called background or images)

    • a background color (in RGBA format, transparent by default)

    In addition layout items contain further layout information, depending on item type:

    • strokes: pen description (drawing color, width, brush and smoothing) and tag ID that references the corresponding ink portion,

    • objects: mime type, position and transformation.

    No transformation information is associated with layout items of type strokes, because ink transformations are stored directly within the ink file.

    The layout stores explicit positioning of elements and thus rendering a page does not require a layout engine. An application may however require a layout engine in order to produce layout of new portions of content.

    Page ink file

    Location

    /pages/abcdefgh/ink.jink (where page id = abcdefgh)

    Description

    This file describes the ink of the page and associated tags, transformations, etc. The .jink files are stored in Jinkson format.

    Page metadata file

    Location

    /pages/abcdefgh/meta.json (where page id = abcdefgh)

    Description

    This metadata file is meant to store information that is specific to that page, in JSON format. By default, no metadata info is set on pages.

    Page InkSearch index file

    Location

    /pages/abcdefgh/ijklm.index (where page ID = abcdefgh, field ID = ijklm)

    Description

    This InkSearch index file is meant to store the indexation information that is specific to that page and to a content field.

    1. We will use two different fonts to refer to objects as multimedia files or objects as instances (in the sense of computer science). We note Objects the multimedia files that can be part of a document. Objects in the sense of computer science will simply be noted objects.

    2. You can also create a pageSelection to specify the ink portion concerned by the recognition process.
